The Sixth Shadow Game

The Frame Game

Core mechanic:
Whoever defines the frame of the game controls how all other moves are interpreted.

It’s not about winning inside the rules.
It’s about shaping the rules, language, and coordinate system people use to think.

Once the frame is accepted, behavior follows automatically.

⸻

What a “frame” actually is

A frame is a compression layer for reality:
	•	language
	•	metaphors
	•	models
	•	categories
	•	coordinate systems

Once people accept a frame, they unknowingly adopt the constraints embedded inside it.

Example:

When people talk about politics as a “left vs right spectrum,” that single metaphor compresses thousands of possibilities into a single axis.

That framing quietly limits how people think about politics.

⸻

Historical examples of frame shifts

Scientific frame shifts

When Isaac Newton introduced classical mechanics, physics began describing the universe through mathematical laws.

Later, Albert Einstein reframed gravity as curved spacetime, fundamentally changing the coordinate system for physics.

The world didn’t change.
The frame describing it did.

⸻

Economic frame shifts

When Adam Smith framed markets as self-regulating systems, it reshaped how societies think about economics.

Policy, institutions, and incentives reorganized around that model.

⸻

Technological frame shifts

Companies like Apple didn’t just build products.

They reframed:
	•	phones → personal computers in your pocket
	•	apps → programmable ecosystems

The frame changed the industry.

